{"/service/ndnp/mb/batch_mb_basil_ver01/data/sn83020847/00517170963/1937123001/0718.xml":{"full_text":"NATIONAL NEWS\nROOSEVELT WARNS\nNAVAL INCREASES\nWILL BE NEEDED\nDisclaims Unfriendly Ges\nture to Any Nation But In\nsists U. S. Must Act\nWashington, Dec. 28 (AP)\nPresident Roosevelt announced a\npossible increase in the naval build\ning program today because, he said,\nthe facts of the troubled world situ\nation \u201care facts and the United\nStates must recognize them.\u201d\nsinking of the American gunboat\nPanay, or any other specific inci\ndent, and disclaiming any unfriend! v\ngesture toward any particular na\ntion, he said merely that recent\nevents had caused him \u201cgrowing\nconcern.\u201d\nOffers So Specific Befalls\nHis intentions were announced ata\nt press conference in which he referred\ncorrespondents to a letter he had\nwritten Chairman Taylor (D\u201e Col.)\nof the House appropriations subcom\nmittee on the navy, advising him that\nhe might expect additional estimates\nfor navy building.\nAt the conference, the President\nanswered a barrage of questions which\nthe reporters fired at him.\nHow many vessels would be added\nto the present program, he could not\nsav. nor could he tell what types of\nship would be constructed. That\ngwaited further study.\nNor did he know whether addi\ntional authorizing legislation wou.d\nbe needed. That, depended on the\ntype of vessel to be built. xf it\nShould be decided to build warships\nfalling into the categories authorized\n|by the Vinson act. new legislation\nwould not be needed\nFor the present, at least, no tn\ncreased naval personnel would be\nnecessary.\n_\n\u201cNot a Preparedness Program\u201d\nAnd one more question:\u2014\n\"Mr President, is this part of a\npreparedness program?\" he was asked.\nTo that, he replied with a qu.et and\ndirect negative.\nThe letter to Taylor, in effect, to.d\nthe latter that the estimates tor naval\nbuilding which will be included in\n.'the budget that goes to Congress next\nweek were to be regarded as incom-\nplate.\n\u201cThe preliminary estimates sub\nmitted by the director of the budget\nto the naval subcommittee were pre\npared some time ago and called for\nappropriations to commence during\nthe fiscal year 1939 (which begins\nnext July 1), two battleships, two\nlight cruisers, eight destroyers and\nsix submarines.\" be wrote.\nUnited States Most Recognise facts\n\"Since that time world events have\ncaused me growing concern. Lnder\nthe constitution the President iscom\nmandef-in-chief of the army and navy\nand has. therefore, a very specific\nduty to safeguard the defense of na\ntional interests.\n\"In speaking of my growing con\ncern I do not refer to any specific\nnation, or to any specific threat,\nagainst the United States. The fact\n\\is that in the world as a whole many\nnations are not only continuing but\nare enlarging their armament pro\ngrams I have used every conceiv\nable effort to stop this trend and to\nwork toward a decrease of armaments.\nFacts, nevertheless, are facts, and the\nUnited States must recognize them.\n\"Will you. therefore, he good\nenough to inform the subcommittee\nor naval appropriations that after\nthe next session of the Congress has\nmet. it is possible that I may sen 1\nsupplementary estimates for com\nmencing construction on a number or\nships additional to the above pro-\ngram.\"\nThe Vinson act, to which Mi\nRoosevelt referred as possibly con\ntaining authorization for the vessels\nhe may ask to have constructed was\npassed in 1934. It authorized the\nconstruction of such vessels as would\nbring the fleet to the strength pro^\nTided under the Washington and\nLondon naval treaties.\nThose treaties are now defunct,\nbut nevertheless the ruling policy\nhas been to adhere to the treaty\nnavy idea. It had been intended\nthat\u2019 the fleet would reach that point\nIn 1942. Some observers were quick\nto express the opinion that Mr Roose\nvelt now wants that level in naval\nstrength reached much more quick\nly.\nThe questioning of reporters\nbrought out that presently contem\nplated increases in the national de\nfense concerned only the construc\ntion of additional ships. The Presi\ndent replied in the negative to a ques\ntion whether be expected to iecom\nmend additions to army or navy\u2019 air\ncorps or to the army itself.\nHe was asked, too. whether the\nnavy yards would participate In the\nnew construction and replied that\nthey would. He did not know, how\never. whether the construction in\nthem of new ways and other facil\nities would be necessary.\nAt the Capitol, most legislators\nwere reluctant to discuss the steo\nimmediately but there were some who\nwere quick to speak their nnnds.\n\"AH I desire to say at this time.'\nsaid Senator Borah of Idaho, rank\ning Republican on the foreign as\nfairs committee, \"is that I sincerely\nhope the President will not find it\nnecessary to call for a large arma-\nmenu outlay.\"\nFrom Senator Wheeler (D.. Mont.)\ncame thia statement;\n*1 see no necessity for spending\nmillions and millions of dollars for\narmaments and battleships when one\nthird of our people are ill-housed.\n111-fed and ill-clothed. (The last clause\nof the sentence was a quotation from\na Roosevelt speech).\n\u201cIf the United States goveinmen\nwill keep out of entangling alliances\nwith Europe, no country or. ths\nglobe is going to attack us. Ther.j\nIs no fear that we will become in\nvolved tn a war unless we permit\nourselves to be led Into It.\"\nOthers Lack Enthusiasm\nSenator Adams (D., Col.) said he\nlacked initial enthusiasm fur the\nIdes\" but \"might be persuaded that\nIt la the thing to do.\" He added\nthat he would reserve judgment, how\never. until a request for additional\nships reaches the appropriations com\nmittee. of which he is a member.\nSenator Johnson (D.. Col.) said he\nwas \"very, very much opposed to\nputting any more money Into the\nnavy,\u201d but that \"If they want to\nbuild some air cruisers for defense\npurposes,\" he would \"support It.\"\nFrom Representative Taylor, the\nrecipient, came this prepared state\nment:\u2014\n\u2018The President's budget is not of\nficially in the hands of Congress and\nuntil It la formally preaented. such\ndetails as have been supplied to my\ncommittee with a view to exi>editin4\nour work must bo treated as con\nfldentlal\n4\nHere Are Eight Words\nThat Tripped Illinois\nChampionship Speller\nSpringfield. 111., Dec. 37\u2014\nThirteen-j ear-old Elaine Meyers\ntoday won the Illinois state spell\ning championship\u2014the little\nblona youngster tripping on\neight words metamorphosis,\nmisogynist. sycophant, fethy\nology, bassinet, limerick, caisson\nand garnishee.\nElaine, her spectacles agleam\nas she heard of her victory,\nlaughed:\n\"I've been studying all sum\nmer for this.\u201d\nCAREER MEN PICKED\nBY U. S. FOR ENVOYS\nIN FASCIST NATIONS\nSending of Hugh Wilson to\nBerlin May Hint Necessity\nof Manning Storm Areas\nWith Skilled Observers\n\nBy KIRKE I* SIMPSON\nWashington. Dec. 28\u2014(AP) The\nnomination of Hugh R. Wilson, now\nI assistant secretary of state, to be\nembassador to Germany is expected\nto reach the Senate early in the regu\nlar session beginning next week.\nWhen he takes his post, all corners\nof the Rome-Berlin-Tokio triangle\nwhich bulks largely in the troubled\ni world scene will have been intrusted\nto career diplomats rather than po\nlitical appointees.\nWhether this marks a definite pol\nicy step by the Roosevelt administra\ntion toward ultimately complete re\nliance on a career foreign service is\na matter of speculation. Most ob\nservers attribute the Wilson selection\nmore to decreasing pressure on the\nWhite House for political diplomatic\nplums. They explain that, in the ordi\nnary course, such political jobs could\nbe expected to last only three years\nbecause President Roosevelt is serving\nhis second term. The career service,\nit is said, has made its most notable,\nadvances, as a rule, in presidential\nsecond terms.\ni There is also speculation as to\nwhether Secretary Hull's expanding\neffort to. rewrite American trade pacts i\nI into a peace-and-commerce arch\ni played any part in Wilson's impend\ning appointment to Berlin. Current i\nnegotiations with the British Com\nmonwealth. regarded at the state de\npartment as the keystone of the arch,\nunquestionably have some bearing on\nthe expected appointment of Joseph\nP. Kennedy to succeed the late Em\nbassador Bingham in London. Work- j\ning out similar agreements with\nRome. Berlin and Tokio at some fu- j\nture date present especially difficult j\nproblems. There is no hint as yet.\nhowever, that more than resumption\nof the Italian-American conversations\ninterrupted by Italy\u2019s Ethiopian cam- j\npaign is in early prospect.\nThe fact that William Phillips, for- J\nmerly undersecretary of state and a i\ncareer service veteran, elected this\nyear to turn to embassadorial duty I\nin Rome, attracted no great attention\nat the time. He took over the post\nlast August at a time when repercus- I\nsions of \u00abhe Italian campaign in Ethi- I\nopia had been supplemented by the j\nSpanish crisis leading to still preva- i\nlent fears that a new world war was\nimpending.\nSelection of another former under\nsecretary and career man. Joseph C.\nGrew, to be embassador to Tokio In I\n1932. came at a time when Japanese-\nAmerican relations were strained over\nManchuria. There was no suggestion.\nwhen the Roosevelt administration\nI came in a year later, of replacing him\nI with a political appointee.\nSEES ROSY FUTURE\nFOR ANTHROPOLOGY\nDr J. K. Shryack Says\nProgress Will Be Made m\nChina Despite the Japa\nnese Invasion\nNew Haven, Ct., Dec. 28\u2014(AP)\u2014\nDr J. K. Shryock, associate editor of\nthe American-Oriental Society Jour\nnal. forecast today a rosy future tor\nanthropolog) in China under the Jap\nanese despite war destruction of folk\nlore possibilities.\n\"The Japanese would not deliberate\n\u0964ly destroy progress in this field in\nI which they are especially interested.\nalthough naturally they would not\nI consider It first.\u201d said Dr Shryock. In\nI attendance at the annual session of\nthe American Anthropological asso\nciation.\n\u2019The Chinese, however, have been\nwaking up in unearthing and preserv\nIng Oriental lore, but the Japanese\nwill be able to intensify their studies\nin the captured areas beyond any\nthing they could do In their own\ncountry, where there are inhabita\ntions.\n\"The war may destroy some of the\nworks already brought to light, be\ncause one does not know what the\nmilitary line will do, but as yet the\nconflict has not reached any of\nthe anthropological diggings, located\nmostly in north China.\"\nHe pointed out that it was obvious\nthat whole towns would be wiped out.\nthereby dcstroylnc much valuable\nfolklore material. Yet. he said. In the\naftermath period the Japanese will\ncarry on what already has been\nstarted with even greater vigor.\n\u201cThey have done some very fine\nwork in the Manchurian sites and\nthe southern Manchurian railroad has\neven erected a library and made a\ncollection of some 7000 volumes deal\ning with that province.\n\u201cWhat railroad would do that In\nAmerica?\"\nDr Shryock. authority on Chinese\nanthropology, delivered a paper be\nfore the association today on the\nI \"Lolo,\u201d a tribe of wild mountain folk\nIn southern China.\n36 MINE TERRORISTS\nGET MAXIMUM TERM\nSpringfield. 111.. Dec. 28\u2014(AP)\nDenjing motion* for a new trial.\nFederal Judge Charles G. Brlggle\ntoday Imposed the maximum penalty\nof four years\u2019 Imprisonment and $20.-\n000 fines on each of the OS defend\nants In the mine and train bombing\nconspiracy case.\nThe defendants were sentenced to\ntwo years and fined SIO,OOO for con\nspiracy to obstruct the mails and one\nyear Imprisonment and SSOOO fine on\neach of two counts charging viola\ntion of the Sherman antitrust act.\nSentences were to run consecutively.\ni.\nTHE SPRINGFIELD WEEKLY REPUBLICAN; SPRINGFIELD, MASS.: THURSDAY, DECEMBER 30, 1937\nPRESIDENT PLAYING\nCAREFUL BUT FIRM\nHAND IN FAR EAST\nOther Nations With Greater\nStakes Said Inclined to Let\nU. S. Take Risks\nBy OWEN L. SCOTT\nWashington, Dec. 25 \u2014Strained rela\ntions between Japan anti the United\nStates, growing from the Japanese at-\nItack on an American gunboat, give\nrise to a variety of questions with\nwhich the executive and members of\nthe Senate are wrestling. Some already\nare answered, others are just, being\nI raised.\nCcrtfcl! Hull, secretary of state, has\niV\u00abA*We 'Sfmiite that ibis Isjjot the\nI time to withdraw American armed\nforces from China. Mr Roosevelt is de\ntermined to obtain from he Japanese\nemperor definite assurances that there\nwill be no repetition of the affront\nmade by Japan to the American na\ntion and that American Interests in\nrChina will be protected. There is to\n|be no hacking water, so far as this\nI government is concerned.\nThe firm course taken by President i\nRoosevelt is drawing support from j\nevery quarter.\ni But there are questions concerning\nthe future of American policy In the\nFar East\u2014aside from the present al\ntercation with Japan\u2014that are begin-\nI ning to be asked and that soon will\njbe demanding an answer. A poll of\nimportant senators and representa-\ni fives reveals a surprising sentiment in\nfavor of withdrawing the armed forces\nof this nation from China. Both houses\nof Congress already have decided that\nwe shall give up the Philippines in a\nfew years. The President hrs observed\nwith\u2019 satisfaction that the American\npeople took calmly the Japanese at\ntack on the gunboat Panay.\nEven so, other questions are being\nraised. Among them are the follow\ning:\u2014\nIs it of primary concern to this na\ntion to try to stop Japan in China?\nAre American Interests as extensive\nas those of other nations which show\na desire to follow rather than to lead\nIn treating with the Japanese in the\nFar East? AVhat could be accom\nplished by a \"quarantine\" of Japan? Is\nthere reason to expect a changed\nAmerican attitude toward the future\njot the Philippine islands?\nThe history of the matter is that\nAmericans played an important part\nin opening both China and Japan to\n1 world trade. President Roosevelt\u2019s an\ncestors were among the traders who\nestablished treaty ports in China, and.\ntor about 80 years, this country has\nmaintained gunboats on the Yangtze\nj and armed forces in socalled treaty\nport cities.\nBut. after all of those years and\nlatter all of the efforts of traders, the\niofficial figures disclose that American\nI exports to China do not average more\nj than 575.000.000 a year\u2014about the I\ncost of one fully equipped, first line\nbattleship. In fact, exports for the\nfirst 10 months of this year were $45.-\n824.000, while imports from China\nwere $89,363,000. American invest\nments in China, principally oil and\ntobacco and church properties, amount\nto about $150,000,000. Fewer than 7000\nAmericans, exclusive of military forces,\nreside in China, and many of those\nhave been evacuated in recent months.\nThis means that, during all of the\nyears of the \"open door\u201d and of word\npictures of the vast markets offered\nby 400.000,000 Chinese customers.\nAmerican interests have done little\npenetrating.\nIf China is scarcely the outlet for\nAmerican capital and American goods\nthat people think it to be. then aren't I\nthe Philippines a reason for this coun-\ntry's deep involvement in the Far j\ni East?\nHere some other facts protrude. The i\nI United States has decided to grant tin- I\n;conditional freedom to the Philippine\nislands in 1946. There is little appar-\nent sentiment in Congress for backing\nI down on that decision. After 1946. the\nI navy will have no interest in defend\ning the Philippines. The army believes\nthem to be just about impossible of\ndefense anyway, because they lie 7000\nmiles from home and are too near\nJapan.\nAn American commission is just\nback from making a study of the abil\nity of the islands, economically, to\nmake the transition to Independence.\nThis commission found ample re\nsources to support the people of the\nPhilippines if the human resources\nproved adequate. Some of the mem\nbers reached the conclusion that, not\nonly could the islands support the\npresent population, but that they could\nprovide a living for 15.000.000 Japanese\non a subsistence farming basis, and\noffered many of the raw materials\nthat Japan most needs. As an invest\nment proposition, these islands looked\nto the American experts as of much\nmore tangible value to Japan than\nany part of China is likely to turn\nout to be.\nBut apparently they have no such\nvalue to the United States.\nProducts of the Philippines com\npete with American farm products.\nTo protect American farmers, we now\nare taxing Philippine sugar and\nI coconut oil imports and are returning\nI the proceeds\u2014about $50,000,000 a\nyear\u2014to the islands. Total exports\nof American products to these pos\nsessions amount to about $100,000,000\na year, of which not more than\n$15,000,000 is profit. And then this\ncountry spends many millions to\nmaintain an army post on the islands\nand it has spent about $100,000,000\non fortifications. Many more millions\nannually are spent to maintain a\nnavy capable of tbeir defense.\nSo here again -the United States\nseems not to have any particular\ntrade or economic reason for be\ncoming deeply Involved in far east\nern affairs.\nIt is different with Great Britain.\nFrance and Holland, all of which\nhave heavy investments in that area\nand none of which is showing any\nintention of sacrificing those In\nterests. The British are heavily In\nvolved in south China. They could\nnot view calmly the establishment\nof Japanese power In the Indian\nocean, what with the Germans al\nready a problem In the North sea\nand Italy threatening In the Medl-\nI terranean But the British have little\ni naval strength in the Pacific and\napparently are counting on the\nUnited States navy.\nPROSECUTOR WON\u2019T\nPROBE HEALY DEATH\nLos Angeles. Dec. 28\u2014(AP)\u2014Dlst-\nAtty Buron Fttts said today he was\nconvinced that the sudden death of\nTed Healy, a week ago, was due to\nnatural causes and that \"as far as\nthis office concerned, there will be\nno further investigation.\"\nHe made this announcement fol\nlowing an Interview in his office with\nMrs Betty Braun Healy, first wife of\nthe comedian, who had declared she\nbelieved Healy might have died from\ninjuries suffered in a reported fight\nIn a Hollywood night club two days\nbefore his death.\nPictures of Attack On. Panay\nComing East by Special Plane\nPrints Will Go to State Department at Washington\u2014\nPublic Will See the Film\nSan Francisco. Dec. 28\u2014(AP) \u2014A\nreel of historic film, picturing the\nI bombing and destruction of the United\nStates gunboat Panay in the Yangtze\nriver, was carried eastward by special\nplane tonight, under the eyes of armed\nguards.\nThe film, stowed In a traveling bag.\nreached here by Clipper plane from\nthe Orient this morning in the care of\nNorman Alley, Universal .Newsreel\nphotographer who was wounded as he\nphotographed the bombing and gun\nning of the Panay by Japanese planes\nDecember 12.\nMore than 20 police and federal\nagents, heavily armed, directed un\nloading. transfer and dispatching of\nthe film, insured for $350,000, The\nnegatives, scheduled to reach New\nYork by 9.30 a. m. (E. S. T.) tomor\nrow. were held up tonight at. Chey\nenne. Wyo,, by dangerous flying\nweather.\nUnited Air Lines officials said the\nplane probably would take off between\n7.30 and 8 a. m. tomorrow (M. S. T.).\nThey said adverse conditions near\nOmaha. Neb., caused the flight delay.\nTwo California state police officers,\nguarding the film aboard the plane,\narranged that the reel should be kept\nat the Cheyenne police station over\nnight. Prints will be sped to the\nstate department at Washington. D. C.,\nand to every corner of the nation for\npublic showing.\n\"There was no possible chance,\"\nAlley declared here, that Japanese i\npilots mistook the Panay for a ship I\nPOWER TUBE STUDY\nTO ENABLE PRECISE\nEFFICIENCY TESTS\n\nHarvard Adds 10-Year Re\nsearch by Dr E. L. Chaffee\nMeans Big Saving for\nRadio Broadcasters\nCambridge, Dec. 28\u2014(AP) \u2014Har-\nvard's scientists tonight announced\na \"major\u201d development enabling them\nto determine with precision the con\nditions of best operation for power\nvacuum tubes, such aseare used in\nradio broadcasting stations.\nThis development, they said, may\nlead to better performance. The ap\nplication of the development to radio.\nhowever, was termed but one of its\nmany uses.\nIt resulted from 10 years of re-\nsearch culminating in the develop-\nment of methods by which the output i\nof the power vacuum tube might be I\nheavily increased.\nAt the same time it was said this I\nresearch would affect the design of\nsuch tubes in the future.\nCan Transmit a Whisper\nThe vacuum tube acts as a means\nof control over electric currents. It\ncan take the whisper of a singer\u2019s\nvoice and send it out over the air to\nhome thousands of miles away. In\nthe X-ray machine It provides the\nphysician with accurate control of\npower.\nThe developments announced to\nnight came from research in the Cruft\nlaboratory of communicatton engineer\ning under direction of Dr E. Leon\nChaffee.\nSpecifically, it was claimed the de- j\nvelopment makes its possible to de- j\ntermine with precision the point at\nwhich a vacuum tube may operate,\nwith maximum efficiency. This would\nautomatically mean a substantial sav-\ning in power bills.\nAbstruse mathematical calculations,\nl backed by routine laboratory tests,\nI were the basis for these conclusions.\nHarvard sources, in relating the\nfindings, said Dr Chaffee\u2019s work \u201cis\nregarded by authorities as a signal\ntriumph of laboratory and mathe\nmatical skill over one of the most\ncomplex problems in electrical engin\neering posed before this generation.\"\nCost Had Been Obstacle\nHeretofore one of the obstacles to\nthe testing of large power tubes has\nbeen their cost, sometimes as much\nas several thousand dollars, and the\nexpensive apparatus necessary. This\nhas been overcome by dimensional\nanalysis. This gives a means of cor\nrelating the results from experiments\non small \"model\u201d tubes and determin\ning from them what the big units\nI will do, a method similar to the build\ning of a model ship before large-scale\nconstruction is undertaken.\nLOW-PRICE STORES\nBAN JAP ARTICLES\nNew York. Dec. 28\u2014 (API\u2014 Two of\nthe nation's largest five and ten-cent\nstore chains \u2014the F. W. Woolworth\ncompany and the S. S. Kresge com\npany-disclosed today their with\ndrawal from the market for Japanese\nmade goods.\n\"Our policy is to buy only mer\nchandise that is acceptable to the\npublic.\" R. R. Williams, vice-president\nin charge of merchandising for the\nKresge company, said in Detroit. T.\nJ. Mullin, assistant to the president\nof the Woolworth chain, said here\nthat the far eastern war was respon\nsible for his company's stand,\n\u201cWhat we have left on our counters\nwas bought and paid for months be\nfore the outbreak of the war,\" Mullin\nsaid, adding his company purchased\nfrom Japan only those articles not\nreadily obtainable on the American\nmarket. These, he said, were not\nmore than one per cent of total pur\nchases.\nWilliams said merchandise his chain\nbought for the holiday trade was\nordered and paid for as far hack as\nlast January. He added: \u201cBoycotts\ncalled suddenly against Japanese mer\nchandise are boycotts against Amer\nican merchants and not against Jap\nanese exporters or manufacturers who\nalready have their money.\u201d\nSome Importers handling Japanese\nbusiness said there had been a no\nticeable decline in Imports of Jap\nanese novelties. An executive of one\nimporting firm said he had noticed a\n\"tremendous\" decline. Some seml-\n1 manufactured goods made of silk, one\nof the chief imports, were affected, he\nsaid.\nDepartment stores handling the\nhigher priced goods reported no let\ndown In sales of lapanese goods. Some\nsaid there had been demonstrations.\nArmour Would Simplify\nCapital Setup Piecemeal\nChicago, Dec. 28\u2014(AP)\u2014Armour\nCo. stockholders be asked at their\nJanuary 28 meeting to modify the\npacking organization's plan for sim\nplification of Its capita! structure, ac\ncording to an announcement today.\ni of other than American registry. \"The\ncolors were painted on the deck and a\nI flag was flying from the mast,\u201d he\nsaid. \"Xhe planes power-dived to\nward us and let loose with bombs and\nI machine guns.\u201d\n\"Both lifeboats from the Panay.\nwhich were machine-gunned, showed\nAmerican flags,\u201d he said. Three\nobservation planes first fl\u2122 over the\ngunboat, Alley related. These were\nfollowed 30 seconds later by the\nbombers.\n\"When the bombers power-dived to\nward the Panay.\u201d he continued, \"at\nthe base of the dive, with the motors\nalmost shut off. I could hear machine\nguns popping from the planes.\u201d\nAlley\u2019s wife and three children met\nhim here, and continued with him to\nNew York in the plane United Air\nLines placed at the service of the\ngovernment. After the Panay bomb\ning, Alley said, he and his party\nwalked 15 miles the first night, to\nHoshien. As soon as the party board\ned the rescue ship Oahu, the pho\ntographer related, \"the films never\nleft navy charge until they arrived\nhere.\u201d\nHe said his\u2019 pictures show the at\ntack by the Japanese planes, the ac\ntual sinking of the Panay, and the\nship being abandoned under fire, as\nwell as the rescue by other vessels.\nThe 43-year-old veteran cameraman\ndescribed the shrapnel injury to his\nright leg as \u201cvery minor.\u201d Asked if\nhe were going back to China, he\nlaughed \"Yeah, maybe in 35 years!\u201d\nStuck in a Chimney,\nSanta Comes Late and\nDisheveled to Party\nSan Antonio, Tex., Dec. 28\n(AP) \u2014The accident children al\nways fear\u2014that Santa Claus might\nget stuck in a chimney\u2014happened\nbefore their very eyes here.\nSanta started down a specially\nbuilt chimney at a Salvation army\nparty last night and became\nwedged in the walls. Frantic at\ntendants finally pulled him down.\nA hundred childish faces, lined\nwith dismay, broke into smiles.\nA disheveled Santa went about\nthe business of distributing gifts.\nSTOCKS LIQUIDATED\nWITH OUTLOOK AND\nNEWS DISCOURAGING\nFeeling Recovery Aid by U.\nS. Is Far Off, Jackson\u2019s\nSpeech, Coming Auto Lay\noff All Cause Decline\nNew York, Dec. 28 \u2014(AP) \u2014Liquida-\ntion swept the stock market today, in\n.continuation of yesterday\u2019s slump,\nand share prices dropped by $1 to $5,\nsome of them to new low levels for\nthe year or longer.\nSelling for tax return purposes, i\ndiscouragement over the business\noutlook and a feeling that new re-\ncovery steps by the government were\nsomewhere in the nebulous distance\ncontributed to the market\u2019s gloom,\nbrokers asserted.\nThey declared Wall street had ap-\npraised the Monday night speech of'\nAsst Atty-Gen Robert H. Jackson as\ndefinitely hurting chances of \"peace\"\nl between the administration and busi\nness leaders, and that this week\u2019s\nsharp additional fall in steel opera\ntions, the 15th in succession, was a\nnew indication of industry's illness.\nAnnouncement that General Motors\nwould lay off 30,000 men January 1\nand rumors other automotive activi\nties soon might be curtailed drasti\ncally were other factors.\nTrading was at the fastest pace\nsince October 29, with 2,381,950 shares\nchanging hands. The ticker tape was\nfrequently behind floor dealings. At\ntimes feeble rallies Interposed to stem\nthe selling tide, but they failed to\nhold.\nAt the finish only 64 stocks of the\n984 traded had recorded advances.\nBut there were 791 declines, while\n129 issues were unchanged for the\nday. There were 166 new lows for the\nyear. The Associated Press average\nof 60 stocks dropped $1.50 at $42.50.\nOn October 19. when It was at its\n1937 low. it touched $41.30. Commodi\ntets generally went the way of stocks.\nSUGGESTS SOLUTION\nOF WAR, POVERTY\nIndianapolis. Dec. 28 \u2014(AP) \u2014A\nscientific solution of the problems of\nwar and poverty was suggested today\nto the American Association for the\nAdvancement nf Science by an agri\ncultural expert.\nSpeaking in the symposium on\nscience and society which the associa\ntion is conducting this week at its\nannual meeting. Gove Hnmhridge, re\nsearch writer of the United States\ndepartment of agriculture. declared\nthat scientists hold the key to solu\ntion of the world\u2019s greatest problems\nIf they will apply the same approach\nused In such fields as medicine, chem\nistry and astronomy.\nIn spite of the advances of science\nwhich have created surpluses In agri\ncultural and other goods so that no\nperson or nation should be poverty\nstricken. Mr Hamhrldge said, there\nare still many individuals who can\nnot afford the minimum diet for\nproper existence and many nations\n\u201cwhich sometimes seem to be on the\nway to smashing civilization\u201d for\nlack of food and other materials.\n\"Science has succeeded.\" he con\ntinued, \"in increasing production to\nthe point where therg is no longer\nany need for much of the poverty and\nsuffering that still plague the world,\nbut the relative abundance created by\nscience threatens periodically to ruin\nus because our social and economic\ninstitutions are not equal to distribut\ning it where It is needed.\u201d\nIndianapolis, Dee. 28\u2014(AP) \u2014The\ntraveling public will be offered air\ntransportation at altitudes of six and\nseven miles with speeds of 275 miles\nan hour and above within the next\nfive years. D. W. Tomlinson, research\ntiler, said today In a paper prepared\nfor presentation before the American\nAssociation for the Advancement of\nScience.\nWithin two years transport service\nwill be. available at hlghts between\ntour and five miles, he added. Sub\nstratosphere experimental aviator for\ntranscontinental and western air.\nTomlinson has been doing research\nwork tor the last four years to deter\nmine what technical difficulties had\nto be overcome and what advantages\ncould be obtained at high altitudes.\n\u2018ENORMOUS\u2019 EXPORT\nOF WAR MATERIALS\nCUSHIONS BUSINESS\nMetals, Gasoline Still Going\nAbroad in. Huge Volumes\n1937 Favorable Trade\nBalance $200,000,000\nWashington, Dec. 28\u2014(A P)\u2014For\neign trade experts of the commerce\ndepartment said today that \"enor\nmous\u201d exports of war materials were\nkeeping American sales abroad at a\nhigh level and providing a cushion\nfor declining business at home.\nAt the same time, they estimated\nthat final figures for 1937 would\nshow that American firms and in\ndividuals sold abroad at least $200.-\n000,000 more in commodities and\nmanufactures than they purchased in\nother lands.\nThis excess of exports, long termed\na \"favorable\u201d balance of trade, would\nrepresent a gain of some $165,000,000\nover 1986, but otherwise would be\nthe smallest \"favorable\u201d balance tn\nthe last six years.\nAsked for an opinion of the year's\nforeign trade developments, one de\npartment expert said:\n\"It's been a great year for prepara\ntion for war.\"\nHe went on to say that exports of\niron and steel, especially scrap, cop\nper and aircraft \"have been enor\nnious,\u201d and that sales of gasoline,\nhave been \"keeping up pretty well,\ntoo.\u201d\n\"Of course you can't fight a modern\nwar without gasoline,\u201d he said.\nTurning to the trends of the last\nmonth or so. he noted that although\ntotal November exports were less\nthan the total for October, there was.\nsimultaneously an against-thc-trend\nIncrease in foreign sales of auto\nmobiles, aircraft and iron and steel\nproducts.\nPreliminary November Figures\nDuring the day the department\nmade public its preliminary figures on\nNovember foreign trade showing total\nexports of $314,682,000, as compared\nwith $332,879,000 in October, and\n$226,364,000 in November of last year\nand total imports of $223,226,000 as\ncompared with $224,391,000 in October\nand $196,400,000 in November of last\nyear.\nThe first 11 months of 1937 showed\ntotal exports of $3,026,872,000 as com\npared with $2,226,178,000 In the same\nperiod of 1936 and total imports of\n$2,375,202,000 this year as compared\nwith $2,177,431,000 last year. Fo r\nthe same period the \"favorable\u201d bal\nance of trade was $151,670,000 this\nyear anS $48,747,000 last year.\n\"Both imports and exports are\nkeeping up surprisingly well, in view\nof the domestic recession,\u201d officials\nsaid.\nNoting that imports dropped some 6\nper cent between October and No\nvember. they attributed the decline,\nin part, to the simple fact that No\nvember had two less business days\nthan October, including the Thanks\ngiving holiday.\nThe drop in total exports was at\ntributed in part \"to smaller shipments\nof agricultural products, notably\nwheat, fruits and tobacco.\u201d While\n\"the quantity of unmanufactured cot\nton exports was slightly larger in\nNovember than in October,\" it was\nsaid, \"the value declined as a result\nof the recession in prices.\"\nFILIPINO KILLS TRIO,\nWOUNDS JO OTHERS\nOakland Dishwasher Taken\nby Police After Homicidal\nTour Which He Blamed\nOn Marital Trouble\nOakland. Cal.. Dec. 28\u2014(AP)\u2014A\nFilipino dishwasher, quoted by police\nas saying he \"went crazy\" when his\nwife left him, killed at least three\ncountrymen and w\u2019ounded 10 others\ntoday In a savage outburst of shoot\ning and stabbing in the Filipino dis\ntrict.\nTwo police officers captured the\nman, booked as Bonifacio Aranda, 28,\nin headquarters of the Philippine As\nsociation of California half an hour\nafter occupants of a three-block area\nhad fled in terror before the assailant.\n\"I don't know why I did it,\u201d Of\nficers Lee Brown and Dan Huge\nquotsl Aranda as declaring. \u201d1 went\ncrazy after my wife left me and I\nsaw her again today downtown.\"\nThose killed tn the bloody foray\nwere: Savero Dulay, 45, a cook; Guz\nman Dolphins, 25, and an unidentified\nFilipino. Police expressed belief one\nother man also had been slain, but\nsome time after order had been re\nstored there were no further reports\nof other dead.\nA report to police said Aranda first\nentered a bakery shop, attacked the\ncook, stabbing him 12 times and then\nslashed a woman three times.\nJoe Bundhi, proprietor of a soft\ndrink establishment, said Aranda\nstabbed two men in his store, and\nlie believed both died. The Filipino\nthen appeared in a drug store and\nstabbed Mary Morales. Bill Kiraze,\na University of California student who\nworks In a barber shop, was wounded,\nnot seriously.\nPolice said a definite list of killed\nand wounded was not immediately\navailable, but said four apparently\nhad died, five or six victims were in\nthe hospital and six others stabbed\ndid not require hospital treatment.\nSAYS FATHER\u2019S GHOST\nORDERED INFANTICIDE\nAnd Henry Nead, Held in\nWisconsin, Is Supported in\nTale by Family\nWisconsin Rapids. Wis., Dec. 27\u2014\nWeird as an incredible tale of fiction\nwas the confession today of a 19-\nyear-old farm laborer that he beat\nhis Infant, foster son to death on the\norders of his father's ghost.\nEqually bizarre was the calm ac\nceptance by other members of the\nfamily of his explanation.\nHis 15-ycar-old child wife and his\nmother botn told authorities that they\nhad seen the ghost on afrcquent oc\ncasions and were satisfied that the\norders from beyond the grave were\nresponsible for the \"sacrifice.\u201d\nThe confessed killer is Henry Nead.\naccording to Sheriff Henry L. Becker\nof Wood county. Nead not only\nblamed the ghost for bringing about\nthe Infanticide, but said that the con\nfession he made of the crime was\nvirtually dictated by the supernatu\nral visitant.\nThe young farmer declared the\nghost of hie father, who died six years\nago, had been hunting him and had\nwarned him \"he was going to cause\nme trouble the re# of my life.\"\nBoulder Dam Lights\nWill Be Turned Off\nWhen Geese Approach\nBoulder City, Nev., Dec, 23\n(AP)\u2014lt'll be a silly goose that\ndoesn't honk when approaching\nBoulder dam.\nA. C. Wingo, division superin\ntendent, reported today night fly\ning geese, blinded by hundreds of\nfloodlights on the power plant, fly\ninto each other, \"fall from great\nhights into the churning waters\nbelow and are often stunned.\"\nWingo said hereafter his men\nwould listen for the honking of\napproaching flocks, and turn off\nthe lights to prevent southward\nflight Interruptions.\nTEMPORARY SILVER\nACCORD SIGNED BY\nU. S. WITH MEXICO\nPact Indicates America May\nContinue to Help Other\nNations Buoy Price\nWashington. Dec. 28 (AP)\u2014A\ntemporary silver agreement with\nMexico indicated tonight that the\nUnited States might continue to col\nlaborate with other nations to buoy\nthe price of the white metal.\nSecretary of the Treasury Morgen\nthau and Mexican Finance Minister\nEduardo Suarez, announced after a\nmorning conference that the United\nStates would continue to buy newly\nmined Mexican silver at a delivered\nprice of 45 cents an ounce through\nJanuary, and would confer again\nabout a longer range program.\nThe understanding involved the\nfirst definite, international commit\nment by the United States for any\nperiod after the London silver agree\nment expires Friday night.\nLondon Accord to Lapse\nThe London agreement, itself, will\nnot be renewed, high officials have\nsaid. In place of such a general\nagreement, the treasury has Indicated\na willingness to negotiate with other\ncountries Individually.\nJust before the outbreak of the\npresent hostilities in the Orient, this\ncountry\u2019 made a new monetary peace\nwith China, agreeing to buy silver\nfrom that country and to sell gold\nto it.\nThe London agreement, ratified by\nthe United States on December 21,\n1933, pledged the United States,\nCanada, Mexico, Peru and Australia\nto absorb 35,000,000 ounces of their\nown silver production annually.\nAmong the countries holding vast\nhoards of old silver, India promised\nnot to sell more than 35.000,000 ounces\nfrom its supplies annually, Spain\nlimited itself to selling 5,000,000 ounces\nannually and China agreed not to sell\nany silver derived from melting up\nits silver coins.\nBy keeping the silver market from\nbeing glutted, the London signatories\nhoped to stabilize and raise the world\nsilver price. The price did rise for\na while, reaching a peak of about 80\ncents an ounce, but eventually sagged\nto the present level of between 42\nand 45 cents an ounce.\nThe agreement had some unexpected\nconsequences. The price got so high\nthat China was forced to abandon its\nsilver monetary standard and thus\ncheapen silver. Spain's internal po\nlitical difficulties interfered with\nSpanish cooperation. Meanwhile,\nMexico, Canada and Peru began look\ning to the United States for an outlet\nfor the silver they were required to\nabsorb.\nAs it turned out, the United States\nupheld the London agreement almost\nsingle-handedly, buying 1.400,000,000\nounces of silver in four years\u2014ap\nproximately 14 tljnes its quota.\nThere is a strong desire in such\nwestern states as Nevada and Utah\nfor high silver prices. These states\nderive much of their wealth and em\nployment from mining sliver and\nother metals whose ore yields silver\nas a by-product.\nThe silver-state spokesmen drew\nsupport from persons who contended\nthe inflationary effect of raising silver\nprices would promote recovery by in\ncreasing the price of farm products\nand other commodities. Immediately\nafter the new deal came into power\nin 1933. these forces combined to tack\ngold and silver provisions onto the\nagricultural adjustment act.\nPrice Expires Friday Night\nUnder this act. President Roosevelt\nfirst decreed a price of 64.64 cents\nan ounce for newly mined domestic\nsilver, and later increased it to 77.67\ncents an ounce. The latter price will\nexpire Friday night, but It has been\npredicted in authoritative circles that\nit would be renewed or replaced by\nsome other figure tn excess of the\nworld price. Mr Roosevelt said today\nthere woul(i be a statement before\nmidnight, Friday.\nIn 1934, Congress passed the silver\npurchase act ordering the treasury to\nacquire stiver until it had one ounce\nfor every three ounces of gold held.\nIn spite of the huge purchases of\nsilver, gold has continued to flow into\nthe treasury so fast that it still needs\n$1,455,000,090 worth of silver to ful\nfill the ratio.\nBecause of this deficiency and be\ncause Congress has shown no inclina\ntion to repeal the ratio, the treasury\nis expected to continue to be one of\nthe world's principal silver buyers.\nCosts Treasury \u201cNothing\"\nTheoretically, the vast silver buy\ning program costs the treasury\nnothing, it pays for the metal with\nsilver certificate currency backed by\nthe silver it buys. These certificates\nare issued only in the amount of the\nsilver purchases, although by law the\ntreasury can Issue $1.29 worth of\nthem for every ounce of silver it\nowns.\nThe treasiiry has declined to Issue\nthe full amount of currency on the\ngrounds that this would be inflation\nary. The difference between th\u00bb\nactual price and $1.29 an ounce repro\nsents a \"profit,\" which the treasury\ncan take and spend at any time.\nELLIOTT ROOSEVELT\nPROMOTED BY HEARST\nNew York. Dec. 27\u2014(AP)\u2014Appoint\nment of Elliott. Roosevelt, son of the\nPresident, as general manager of\nHearst Radio, Inc., was announced to\nday by Joseph V. Connolly, chairman\nof the board.\nYoung Roosevelt, has been vice\npresident and general manager of\nSouthwest stations of the Hearst\nchain. In his now post, which he\nassumes January 1, he will be located\nIn New York.\nHe Is the second member of the\nRoosevelt circle to be connected with\nHearst enterprises. The President's\nson-in-law, John Boettiger, is pub\nlisher of W. R. Hearst's Seattle Poet-\nIntelllgencer.\nNATIONAL NEWS\nKNUDSEN HOPES\n30,000 LAYOFF\nWONT BE LONG\nGeneral Motors Three-Day\nWeek Forced by Lack of\nBuying Power, President\nSays U. A. W. Leader\nBlames Big Business\nDetroit, Dec. 28\u2014(AP) \u2014General\nMotors corporation announced to\nday that because of the \u201crecesston\nin business\u201d approximately 30,000\nemployes in its automotive plants\nin the United States would be laid\noff effective January 1-\nWilliam S. Knudsen, president,\nwho made the announcement, said\nno plant would be closed completely,\nand that the workers retained would\nwork a 24-hour, three-day week.\nChrysler, Ford Also Retrenching\nOthers of the \"big three\u201d of the in\ndustry also have curtailed operations.\nIn Chrysler's Detroit plants, which\nhave operated on a four-day, 32-hour\nwork week, assembly lines will be\nidle until after January 1. Ford\nsources reported that about 40,000 of\na normal 87,000 employes are working\nthis week at the huge Dearborn plant.\nFord assembly lines are not operating\nbut their resumption is planned tenta\ntively for next week.\nDespite the announced layoff. Knud\nsen said, \"there will still remain on\nGeneral Motors pay roll in the United\nStates more than 205.000 men. and the\nmonthly pay roll will exceed $24,000,-\n000.\" He said January production\nwould total about 90,000 units, do\nmestic and export.\nAccumulated inventories, \"both in\nthe field and at the plants.\" he said,\n\"have reached a point where adjust\nment must take place.\"\nKnudsen explained 20,000 General\nMotors dealers have on hand about\n60.000 more cars than at this time last\nyear, and that dealers in the Industry\nas a whole have stocks of about 600,-\n000 used cars which he estimated to be\n150,000 to 200,000 higher than last\nyear.\n\u201cThe used car market is stopped,\"\nhe said, \"and when that is stopped\nour employment stops.\u201d\nApproximately 20.000 of those to be\nlaid off are employed in the corpora\ntion's Michigan's plants, Knudsen\nsaid. Local managers in plants else\nwhere will arrange the reduction in\nworking forces, which he said would\nbe made by seniority according to an\nagreement with the United Automo\nbile Workers' union. There will be\nno reductions in G. M. plants in Can\nada. Knudsen said, because \"business\nIs normal there.\u201d\nAsked If price revisions on new cars\nmight ease the marketing problem,\nthe General Motors official said, \"a\ncheaper market will do no good if we\ncan't sell used cars. Purchasing\npower is down.\"\nFrankensteen Comments Sharply\nRichard T. Frankensteen, assistant\npresident of the U. A. W.. commented\non the announcement with the state\nment: \"Whenever industrialists fail to\nsolve, the problems which they them\nselves have created, their first step is\nto throw men into the streets.\nThe real fact of the matter is that\nlabor hasn't received sufficient to pur\nchase the products they are making.\"\nFrankensteen, recently appointed by\nGov Frank Murphy to Michigan's\nEmergency Welfare commission, said\nthe U. A. W. would \"see to it that our\npeople stick together, and go after\nwelfare for them since they are en\ntitled to it,\u201d\nGeneral Motors\u2019 announcement of\nthe layoff came almost on the anni\nversary of the start of last winter\u2019s\nsit-down strikes at Flint, Mich.. De\ncember 30. and of the \"stop orders\u201d to\nthe corporation\u2019s suppliers issued on\nthat same date.\nNEW DEAL LIKELY\nTO BATTLE CRITICS\nSigns of Aggressive Fight\nSeen as It Is Announced\nIckes Plans Radio Talk On\n\u2018lt Is Happening Here\u2019\nWashington, Dec. 28\u2014(AP) \u2014Signs\nthat the administration would make\nan aggressive fight against its busi\nness critics Increased today when it\nwas announced that Secretary Ickes\nwould speak by radio Thursday night\non the subject, \"It is happening here\u201d\nAssociates of the sharp-tongued\nchief of the interior department said\nthey expected the address to deal with\nrelations between government and\nbusiness. Ickes is scheduled to speak\nover a coast-to-coast network at 8\np. m. t eastern standard time.\nHis broadcast will follow by only\na few days a speech In which Robert\nH. Jackson, assistant attorney-gen\neral, charged that monopolies had\ncaused the business slump by increas\ning prices excessively.\nF. B. R. May Fight For Laws\nIt may give added significance to\nrecent reports that President Roose\nvelt, Instead of abandoning adminls.\ntratlon policies blamed by some busi\nness spokesmen for the recession,\nwould make a vigorous fight for com\npletion of his legislative program at\nthe regular session of Congress ba\nginning next week.\nSuch reports spread through the\nCapitol after a conference between\nthe President and a group of hit\nSenate supporters.\nPresidential aids announced today\nthat the President's annual message\nto Congress would be delivered Mon\nday, the first day of the new ses\nsion. They said it had not been de\ncided whether Mr Roosevelt would\ndeliver the message In person. How.\never, Senator Barkley of Kentucky,\nthe Democratic leader, recently ex\npressed belief that the message would\nbe delivered In person.\nMay Deliver It In Person\nThe President said at a press con\nference later today that he thought\nhe would deliver his message in per\nson.\nAnother communication, his annual\nbudget message, will go to the Capi\ntol Tuesday or Wednesday.\nHe said he had no other state\nments. or speeches. In mind except\nan address. January 8. before ths\nannual Jackson-day dinner here.\nMr Roosevelt declared there was a\nlot In what. Bernard M. Baruch, New\nYork Industrialist, told reporters after\nlunching with him today.\nBaruch had said ths nation could\npull out of the business slump if it\ndisplayed wisdom and forbearance.\nThe President would not comment\non the announcement by a\nMotors that It would lay oB W.oO#\nmen January L","height":"25943","width":"20145"}}
